1
00:00:31,031 --> 00:00:32,294
The timing was good.

2
00:00:32,366 --> 00:00:34,062
I just got a job transfer.

3
00:00:34,134 --> 00:00:36,000
Gretchen will start
at a new school.

4
00:00:36,803 --> 00:00:40,069
We're gonna start a whole
new life. It's very exciting.

5
00:00:40,140 --> 00:00:42,371
In college, my dad
majored in cheerleading.

6
00:00:45,312 --> 00:00:46,336
That was a joke.

7
00:00:46,680 --> 00:00:48,200
Gretchen's got a
great sense of humor.

8
00:00:48,782 --> 00:00:50,045
I'm laughing on the inside.

9
00:00:50,884 --> 00:00:53,149
Soon, you'll be laughing
on the outside, too.

10
00:00:53,220 --> 00:00:54,415
Dr. Park?

11
00:00:54,488 --> 00:00:56,548
Moebius syndrome
is the paralysis

12
00:00:56,623 --> 00:00:59,320
of the sixth and seventh
pair of cranial nerves.

13
00:00:59,393 --> 00:01:01,794
The seventh pair
controls facial expression.

14
00:01:01,862 --> 00:01:02,989
Luckily, in Gretchen's case,

15
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:05,023
we haven't found any
limitation to the sixth pair.

16
00:01:05,499 --> 00:01:06,831
I'm a lucky girl.

17
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:09,495
We'll be taking two slivers
of muscle from your thighs,

18
00:01:09,570 --> 00:01:11,300
along with their nerves
and blood supply,

19
00:01:11,371 --> 00:01:12,815
and transplanting
them into your cheeks.

20
00:01:12,839 --> 00:01:14,217
There will be
considerable recovery time

21
00:01:14,241 --> 00:01:16,107
before you'll be
able to smile at will.

22
00:01:16,176 --> 00:01:17,576
Maybe three months.

23
00:01:18,979 --> 00:01:21,244
So what do you say?
Are you up for this?

24
00:01:22,516 --> 00:01:23,540
Can I sleep on it?

25
00:01:25,385 --> 00:01:27,115
See what I have to live with?

26
00:01:27,187 --> 00:01:28,621
Nobody knows when I'm joking.

27
00:01:28,689 --> 00:01:31,818
Sorry, Dr. Andrews.
Yes, I am very up for this.

28
00:01:31,892 --> 00:01:34,862
Ah, okay. Great. So, unless
there are any other questions...

29
00:01:34,928 --> 00:01:37,261
Do you want to be a comedian?

30
00:01:39,866 --> 00:01:43,166
People getting your jokes
must be very important to you

31
00:01:43,236 --> 00:01:47,071
if you think it's worth the risk
of dying during elective surgery.

32
00:01:54,748 --> 00:01:55,875
Hmm.

33
00:02:06,026 --> 00:02:08,052
I apologize for Dr. Murphy.

34
00:02:08,128 --> 00:02:10,825
He's still learning that
silence is the right choice

35
00:02:10,897 --> 00:02:12,729
when you have
nothing useful to offer.

36
00:02:12,799 --> 00:02:14,631
We are required

37
00:02:14,968 --> 00:02:17,494
to have an honest
risk-benefit discussion

38
00:02:17,571 --> 00:02:18,903
with our patients.

39
00:02:19,139 --> 00:02:21,199
We are giving a lovely
young girl a smile.

40
00:02:21,274 --> 00:02:22,333
That's a simple equation.

41
00:02:22,409 --> 00:02:24,571
Well, it's more than
the smile or the jokes.

42
00:02:25,278 --> 00:02:27,873
She can't express
any emotions at all.

43
00:02:28,215 --> 00:02:32,619
No one can tell if she's
happy or sad or scared.

44
00:02:32,986 --> 00:02:34,477
Anything.

45
00:02:34,554 --> 00:02:36,386
She's never had
much of a social life.

46
00:02:36,456 --> 00:02:40,416
Ever since her mother died,
she's been completely withdrawn.

47
00:02:42,729 --> 00:02:46,325
All I wanna do is bring my
baby girl back into the world.

48
00:02:47,434 --> 00:02:50,768
Don't worry, Mr. Milman, we'll
take great care of her, all right?

49
00:02:55,942 --> 00:02:58,571
Lucy has a post-op
infection of unknown origin.

50
00:02:58,645 --> 00:03:00,944
Infusing 900 milligrams
of clindamycin.

51
00:03:01,448 --> 00:03:02,609
It's terrible, isn't it?

52
00:03:03,483 --> 00:03:04,542
Yes, it is.

53
00:03:04,618 --> 00:03:05,962
Have you been
changing your dressing?

54
00:03:05,986 --> 00:03:07,045
Every day.

55
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:08,952
- Soaking it in clean, warm water?
- Yes.

56
00:03:09,022 --> 00:03:11,514
Taking your antibiotics,
one pill three times a day?

57
00:03:12,292 --> 00:03:13,316
That's a no.

58
00:03:15,195 --> 00:03:17,960
Lucy, I know I gave
you a script for antibiotics

59
00:03:18,031 --> 00:03:19,142
along with one for pain meds.

60
00:03:19,166 --> 00:03:20,926
Why haven't you been
taking your antibiotics?

61
00:03:22,269 --> 00:03:24,636
Did you have a bad
reaction to them or...

62
00:03:25,839 --> 00:03:27,705
I never filled my prescription.

63
00:03:28,975 --> 00:03:32,036
I didn't think it was
necessary until it got really bad,

64
00:03:32,112 --> 00:03:34,581
and then I was too
weak to go myself,

65
00:03:34,648 --> 00:03:36,583
and I didn't have anyone
to pick it up for me.

66
00:03:36,650 --> 00:03:38,278
Okay, mystery solved.

67
00:03:40,854 --> 00:03:42,982
I'm sorry. I know it was stupid.

68
00:03:43,056 --> 00:03:44,183
Very stupid.

69
00:03:57,738 --> 00:03:59,229
Okay.

70
00:04:00,006 --> 00:04:01,030
Hey, Shaun.

71
00:04:02,743 --> 00:04:05,577
- Oh, hello.
- Haven't seen you in ages.

72
00:04:05,645 --> 00:04:06,669
What's... What's new?

73
00:04:07,748 --> 00:04:10,343
- I'm buying an apple.
- I can see that.

74
00:04:10,417 --> 00:04:12,977
- Here, I'll... I'll get it for you.
- No, thank you.

75
00:04:13,053 --> 00:04:14,419
- Thank you, Shaun.
- Yes.

76
00:04:14,488 --> 00:04:15,854
What else is new?

77
00:04:16,156 --> 00:04:18,148
You didn't want to be friends.

78
00:04:18,759 --> 00:04:20,022
Mmm.

79
00:04:20,093 --> 00:04:23,188
Yeah, no, uh, we...
We're colleagues.

80
00:04:23,497 --> 00:04:24,658
You know, we're...

81
00:04:24,731 --> 00:04:26,962
Whatever we are, we can
still talk. We should talk.

82
00:04:27,033 --> 00:04:29,002
I have a new friend. Kenny.

83
00:04:29,069 --> 00:04:30,264
Here you go.

84
00:04:30,837 --> 00:04:34,274
Thank you, Debbie. Kenny,
huh? That's, uh... That's great.

85
00:04:34,341 --> 00:04:36,003
Do you have a new friend?

86
00:04:38,178 --> 00:04:40,545
- No.
- Okay.

87
00:04:40,614 --> 00:04:41,946
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

88
00:04:43,116 --> 00:04:45,278
We can talk, you know?
We can talk about sports.

89
00:04:45,352 --> 00:04:46,763
We can talk about
weather. We can talk about...

90
00:04:46,787 --> 00:04:48,016
Debbie?

91
00:04:48,088 --> 00:04:49,365
Why would you wanna
talk about Debbie?

92
00:04:49,389 --> 00:04:50,789
Debbie was flirting with you.

93
00:04:52,025 --> 00:04:53,049
She was?

94
00:04:53,426 --> 00:04:56,590
Yes, I noticed her
exhibiting two typical signs.

95
00:04:56,797 --> 00:04:58,823
- Not the trifecta, though?
- No, not the trifecta.

96
00:04:58,899 --> 00:05:00,231
And one atypical sign.

97
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:01,577
I think she's just
trying to be friendly.

98
00:05:01,601 --> 00:05:04,070
She gave you an
extra dollar in change.

99
00:05:05,906 --> 00:05:09,365
And the fact that you didn't
notice means you like her, too.

100
00:05:11,745 --> 00:05:14,271
Maybe she's just bad at math.

101
00:05:21,555 --> 00:05:23,615
My dad said that
you're on the spectrum.

102
00:05:24,324 --> 00:05:26,987
That's why you said that
about people getting my jokes.

103
00:05:27,060 --> 00:05:29,222
People always get my jokes.

104
00:05:29,763 --> 00:05:30,890
Then you're very lucky.

105
00:05:33,266 --> 00:05:34,325
That was a joke.

106
00:05:35,435 --> 00:05:36,630
I see what you did there.

107
00:05:37,337 --> 00:05:38,464
Yes.

108
00:05:41,141 --> 00:05:44,578
They call me
"Resting Gretch Face."

109
00:05:46,913 --> 00:05:49,075
"Shaun the Moron."

110
00:05:51,484 --> 00:05:55,080
Not very witty. No, I'm
obviously quite smart.

111
00:05:55,155 --> 00:05:56,783
I drew this to their attention.

112
00:06:01,161 --> 00:06:02,322
I'm on a spectrum, too.

113
00:06:04,698 --> 00:06:08,601
It's somewhere between
inscrutable, unapproachable,

114
00:06:10,036 --> 00:06:11,436
and actively scorned.

115
00:06:11,771 --> 00:06:14,331
I don't want to be
more approachable,

116
00:06:14,608 --> 00:06:19,569
and I prefer people not reading
my emotions. They're mine.

117
00:06:19,646 --> 00:06:21,444
But that's what
you do with friends.

118
00:06:30,857 --> 00:06:33,326
You really think this
surgery's too risky?

119
00:06:33,460 --> 00:06:36,589
Possible complications
include embolism, hemorrhage,

120
00:06:36,663 --> 00:06:40,794
collateral paralysis, asymmetry,
brain damage, and stroke.

121
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:47,202
It's also expensive and
medically unnecessary.

122
00:06:48,875 --> 00:06:50,810
Okay. Look straight ahead.

123
00:06:53,647 --> 00:06:56,412
There's a two-hour wait in
the ER, and what are we doing?

124
00:06:56,483 --> 00:06:59,351
Treating a woman because she
wilfully ignored doctors' orders.

125
00:06:59,419 --> 00:07:02,218
I know what a parasite
looks like, and it's not Lucy.

126
00:07:02,522 --> 00:07:04,150
So this is a mom thing with you.

127
00:07:04,324 --> 00:07:06,623
Growing up with a whack
mother means that you can identify

128
00:07:06,693 --> 00:07:08,321
any and all problem
personalities.

129
00:07:08,395 --> 00:07:11,797
And that is the sole upside to my
miserable childhood. Thank you.

130
00:07:11,865 --> 00:07:14,767
Well, at least you had a
mom. Mine died when I was six,

131
00:07:14,834 --> 00:07:16,545
and Dad instantly
married a child-hating bitch

132
00:07:16,569 --> 00:07:18,367
with a butt-load of debt.

133
00:07:19,339 --> 00:07:20,671
Morgan, I'm sorry. I...

134
00:07:20,740 --> 00:07:23,904
I didn't tell you to get sympathy.
Just that I know parasites, too.

135
00:07:31,418 --> 00:07:33,512
Got you booked first
thing tomorrow morning.

136
00:07:34,387 --> 00:07:35,480
Dad.

137
00:07:35,555 --> 00:07:37,683
- What? Too soon?
- It's...

138
00:07:37,958 --> 00:07:39,358
You're nervous.

139
00:07:40,193 --> 00:07:41,388
I get it.

140
00:07:41,795 --> 00:07:44,128
If you have any more
questions, feel free.

141
00:07:46,266 --> 00:07:47,791
I've changed my mind.

142
00:07:50,537 --> 00:07:52,199
I'm not having the surgery.

143
00:08:03,049 --> 00:08:04,108
Murphy.

144
00:08:08,588 --> 00:08:09,612
Hello.

145
00:08:12,225 --> 00:08:14,217
Gretchen's father is very upset.

146
00:08:14,728 --> 00:08:16,594
Seems you talked
her out of the surgery.

147
00:08:16,663 --> 00:08:19,997
No, I didn't talk her out
of it or talk her anywhere.

148
00:08:20,066 --> 00:08:22,501
I just gave her the
list of potential risks.

149
00:08:22,736 --> 00:08:25,706
Embolism, hemorrhage,
collateral paralysis, asymmetry,

150
00:08:25,772 --> 00:08:27,206
brain damage, and stroke.

151
00:08:27,273 --> 00:08:30,107
- "Stroke"?
- Yes. There was a case in Brazil

152
00:08:30,176 --> 00:08:32,577
- in 2004, and the patient suffered...
- Uh... Uh...

153
00:08:34,447 --> 00:08:37,884
It seems that you don't believe
that restoring this girl's smile

154
00:08:37,951 --> 00:08:38,975
is that important.

155
00:08:39,419 --> 00:08:43,550
Smiles are overvalued. There
are studies that support that.

156
00:08:43,623 --> 00:08:44,943
And there are
studies that don't.

157
00:08:45,792 --> 00:08:49,229
When we smile, we produce
endorphins. They make us happy.

158
00:08:49,295 --> 00:08:50,456
They make other people happy.

159
00:08:50,530 --> 00:08:51,589
When we see smiles,

160
00:08:51,664 --> 00:08:55,465
our basotemporal lobes are
activated, and we duplicate what we see.

161
00:08:55,535 --> 00:08:57,800
Murphy, smiles are contagious.

162
00:08:58,271 --> 00:08:59,295
You see?

163
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:05,010
I feel good. You feel good.
Everybody likes smiles.

164
00:09:08,815 --> 00:09:09,839
I don't.

165
00:09:10,617 --> 00:09:12,950
In any case, your
smile wasn't sincere

166
00:09:13,019 --> 00:09:15,386
since it didn't demonstrate
the Duchenne marker.

167
00:09:15,455 --> 00:09:16,616
There was no involvement

168
00:09:16,689 --> 00:09:19,557
of the <i>orbicularis oculi</i>
muscles around the eyes,

169
00:09:19,626 --> 00:09:21,618
which means you didn't
release endorphins.

170
00:09:22,896 --> 00:09:26,230
You know, if you can talk her out
of a surgery she's wanted for years,

171
00:09:26,299 --> 00:09:28,996
I'm pretty sure a conversation
with someone objective

172
00:09:29,069 --> 00:09:30,401
can talk her back into it.

173
00:09:30,470 --> 00:09:33,634
Get Park, come
with, and keep quiet.

174
00:09:35,141 --> 00:09:36,200
Okay.

175
00:09:40,580 --> 00:09:41,639
Dr. Kalu.

176
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:44,384
Remember me?

177
00:09:45,151 --> 00:09:46,175
Fish girl?

178
00:09:46,252 --> 00:09:48,653
- Uh, hi. Celez, hi.
- Yeah.

179
00:09:48,721 --> 00:09:50,883
Yes, of course I do.

180
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:53,188
Hope it's okay that
I requested you.

181
00:09:53,259 --> 00:09:56,229
I'm glad you did.
How are you doing?

182
00:09:56,696 --> 00:09:59,165
Ooh, that's what
you're going to tell me.

183
00:10:00,934 --> 00:10:03,426
I've been wearing the, uh,
tilapia skins for five months.

184
00:10:05,371 --> 00:10:08,603
I'm getting really tired of being
followed home by stray cats.

185
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:10,270
How's the pain?

186
00:10:10,343 --> 00:10:13,336
Compared to what
it was? Nothing.

187
00:10:15,682 --> 00:10:19,119
- Uh, any fever, itchiness, or swelling?
- Nope.

188
00:10:19,185 --> 00:10:20,551
Well, it looks very good.

189
00:10:21,054 --> 00:10:22,113
But...

190
00:10:23,590 --> 00:10:25,183
How much longer?

191
00:10:25,758 --> 00:10:27,124
Um...

192
00:10:27,193 --> 00:10:29,458
How do you feel about tomorrow?

193
00:10:31,764 --> 00:10:34,427
- Seriously?
- I never joke about tilapia.

194
00:10:39,639 --> 00:10:40,971
What's the matter?

195
00:10:41,374 --> 00:10:43,866
I... I just wasn't
expecting that.

196
00:10:45,211 --> 00:10:46,304
I...

197
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:51,084
I'm afraid of how
I'm going to look.

198
00:10:53,086 --> 00:10:54,326
You're going to look beautiful.

199
00:10:59,058 --> 00:11:00,082
Tomorrow.

200
00:11:01,995 --> 00:11:04,863
I know Dr. Murphy informed
you about the risks of this surgery,

201
00:11:04,931 --> 00:11:08,333
and some risks are
significant, and some just aren't.

202
00:11:08,768 --> 00:11:11,602
This is as close to risk-free
surgery as we can get.

203
00:11:12,572 --> 00:11:15,770
It'll give you a smile.
It'll let you laugh.

204
00:11:15,842 --> 00:11:16,901
No.

205
00:11:17,110 --> 00:11:20,080
Dr. Murphy didn't
talk me out of it.

206
00:11:22,015 --> 00:11:23,449
He inspired me.

207
00:11:26,452 --> 00:11:29,479
He helped me realize that this
could actually make me stronger.

208
00:11:31,658 --> 00:11:33,320
I don't wanna run
from it anymore.

209
00:11:44,204 --> 00:11:45,797
She's lying.

210
00:11:46,806 --> 00:11:48,775
She's a smart,
sarcastic young woman,

211
00:11:48,841 --> 00:11:51,777
not exactly someone who's
prone to inspirational stories.

212
00:11:51,844 --> 00:11:53,155
Why would she lie
about changing her mind?

213
00:11:53,179 --> 00:11:54,238
Well, when I was a cop,

214
00:11:54,314 --> 00:11:56,659
I had a lot of people change
their minds about testifying in court,

215
00:11:56,683 --> 00:11:58,652
and it always came down
to one of three reasons.

216
00:11:58,818 --> 00:12:01,652
Fear, confusion, or
they were paid off.

217
00:12:02,622 --> 00:12:04,833
- She doesn't seem confused.
- And I don't think she's afraid.

218
00:12:04,857 --> 00:12:06,883
So Gretchen was paid off?

219
00:12:07,193 --> 00:12:09,128
I admit the
analogy isn't perfect.

220
00:12:10,163 --> 00:12:11,995
It's close enough.

221
00:12:21,007 --> 00:12:22,737
Guess who's back in the ER.

222
00:12:23,743 --> 00:12:27,043
You're happy, so I'm guessing
it's a non-compliant patient.

223
00:12:27,747 --> 00:12:29,409
You misjudged Lucy.

224
00:12:29,482 --> 00:12:32,179
She made an honest mistake
forgetting her prescriptions.

225
00:12:32,752 --> 00:12:34,186
You called her, didn't you?

226
00:12:34,254 --> 00:12:37,349
She didn't spontaneously
remember. You had to remind her.

227
00:12:38,224 --> 00:12:39,920
Is that a mom thing, too?

228
00:12:40,360 --> 00:12:41,692
Gretchen.

229
00:12:42,362 --> 00:12:44,729
Are you worried that your
dad can't afford this surgery?

230
00:12:44,864 --> 00:12:46,890
The insurance
company is paying for it.

231
00:12:48,501 --> 00:12:51,369
Dad, I know it isn't.

232
00:12:52,071 --> 00:12:53,095
It's elective.

233
00:12:54,073 --> 00:12:56,008
It's medically unnecessary.

234
00:12:56,876 --> 00:12:59,402
No one can put a
value on your smile.

235
00:13:00,380 --> 00:13:02,281
Not bullies, not an
insurance company,

236
00:13:02,348 --> 00:13:03,441
not even Dr. Murphy.

237
00:13:05,084 --> 00:13:08,680
In my opinion, this surgery
is medically necessary.

238
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:16,256
Gretchen, sweetie,

239
00:13:17,397 --> 00:13:19,423
my first memory of your mother

240
00:13:20,433 --> 00:13:22,800
was of her smiling at
me from across the room.

241
00:13:23,970 --> 00:13:25,461
And because of that smile,

242
00:13:26,572 --> 00:13:27,596
we ended up with you.

243
00:13:29,075 --> 00:13:31,772
And my last memory of her

244
00:13:32,145 --> 00:13:36,207
is that radiance lighting
up the world one last time.

245
00:13:40,253 --> 00:13:41,983
I mean, we never had much money,

246
00:13:42,755 --> 00:13:46,954
but as long as I had
that smile, it didn't matter.

247
00:13:53,099 --> 00:13:54,158
I love you, Dad.

248
00:13:56,602 --> 00:14:00,164
And that's why I can't let
you give up everything for this.

249
00:14:11,951 --> 00:14:14,420
- Lucy Callard?
- I'm here.

250
00:14:17,290 --> 00:14:18,588
Um...

251
00:14:18,658 --> 00:14:20,957
Lucille Elizabeth Callard?

252
00:14:21,661 --> 00:14:22,720
Yes, that's me.

253
00:14:22,795 --> 00:14:25,094
A Dr. Browne called me
to pick up my prescriptions.

254
00:14:32,271 --> 00:14:34,570
You're the victim of
identity theft, Lucy.

255
00:14:34,640 --> 00:14:37,804
There's an impostor using your
name and medical ID to get benefits.

256
00:14:38,010 --> 00:14:39,521
Did you have your
purse stolen recently?

257
00:14:39,545 --> 00:14:40,672
Six weeks ago.

258
00:14:41,514 --> 00:14:43,881
And you had your driver's
license and credit cards replaced,

259
00:14:43,950 --> 00:14:45,350
but not your health
insurance card?

260
00:14:46,652 --> 00:14:49,383
